description:
WHY: house pipeline step 3 - and deliberately the FIRST new mechanism built on the A1 AttentionCore scaffolding, doubling as the refactor's acceptance test: if adding framework #12 takes more than ~150 LOC of pure math, A1 has not delivered its promise (measure and record the LOC in close notes).

WHAT: nanochat/clifford_attention_torch.py (new file consistent with the per-mechanism file pattern) implementing the F1 design on the A1 scaffold:
- Multivector interpretation of head_dim (chunks of blade_count; constraint head_dim % blade_count == 0 validated at config time with actionable error);
- rotor-gate aggregation per F1 (reuse the octonion chunking pattern for memory bounds - octonion_attention_torch.py precedent);
- dispatch entry in gpt.py Block; --attention-type clifford in train.py; GPTConfig field(s) for algebra selection if F1 kept both Cl(2,0)/Cl(3,0) options;
- KV-cache via the standard scaffolding (no special lanes needed);
- buffer stats: mean rotor norm deviation (diagnostic, D2 stream).

VERIFICATION INTEGRATION (non-negotiable):
- B1 certify entries: rotor norm preservation; quaternion-reduction spot check (configure the algebra to the quaternion-isomorphic case, compare against quaternion attention outputs numerically); causality; non-degenerate grade mixing (grade-projection energy not collapsing to scalars after init);
- KV-cache parity test in tests/test_demos.py (the standard full-vs-incremental pattern);
- B2 property tests for the torch multiplication table (same laws as the JAX demo checks).

BENCHMARK INTEGRATION: added to bench-fixed-flops variant lists, the C4 scorecard mechanism set (predictions already preregistered via F1->C3), and the E1 ladder feasibility table.

ACCEPTANCE: trains on CPU smoke config; certify green; KV parity green; one recorded fixed-FLOPs A/B vs quaternion (the most informative single comparison - same family, more structure) in artifacts/.

DEPENDS ON: F1 (design), A1 (scaffold - this is its first consumer).

WHY: house pipeline step 3 for framework #13; completes the three-way hierarchy-bias comparison set (hyperbolic vs ultrametric vs fractal) for the C4 scorecard.

WHAT: nanochat/hyperbolic_attention_torch.py on the A1 scaffold:
- Lorentz-model scoring (-d_H/tau) and tangent-space value aggregation per F4; learnable per-head curvature c (parameterized as softplus to stay positive; init per F4);
- NUMERICS DISCIPLINE (governed by F4's numerics section): Minkowski inner products and exp/log maps computed in fp32 even under bf16 autocast (explicit .float() islands with cast-back); constraint projection after parameter updates where applicable; clamps at the documented thresholds with B4-style fuzz coverage;
- KV-cache via standard scaffolding; GQA supported;
- buffer stats for D2: per-head learned curvature values, mean hyperbolic radius of embeddings (interpretability: is the model actually using the curvature? c collapsing to ~0 means "it learned to be Euclidean" - an honest and interesting outcome to report).

VERIFICATION INTEGRATION:
- B1 certify entries: Lorentz constraint residual; c->0 reduction vs standard attention (set c tiny, compare outputs); causality; exp/log round-trip at production shapes;
- KV parity test (test_demos.py pattern); B4 fuzz cells for the saturation-prone ops;
- B2 property tests where laws are exact.

BENCHMARK INTEGRATION: scorecard mechanism set with the F4-preregistered predictions; HEADLINE: hierarchical-retrieval three-way (hyperbolic / ultrametric / fractal) plus standard baseline, equal FLOPs, >=3 seeds - this single table is the epic's payoff and should be called out in the C4 report.

ACCEPTANCE: trains CPU smoke; certify green incl. the c->0 reduction; KV parity green; the three-way comparison recorded in artifacts/ when C4 infrastructure is available (otherwise via bench-fixed-flops directly).

DEPENDS ON: F4 (design), A1 (scaffold).

WHY: a "production transformer implementation" that has never generated text for a user is not credible, and the decode paths (trie-mode ultrametric CPU decode, simplicial y1 cache, braid discrete schedules, quaternion/octonion rotor math under KV-cache) have unit-test parity coverage but ZERO in-anger end-to-end exercise. Generation is also the demo-able artifact for the README and the qualitative-comparison tool for mechanisms.

WHAT: `mgr sample --checkpoint DIR --prompt "..." [--max-tokens N] [--temperature T] [--top-k K] [--seed S] [--device]`:
- loads via D1, generates with the existing generate() (gpt.py), streams tokens to a rich live display, reports tokens/s and peak memory at the end;
- comparison mode: `mgr sample --compare ckptA ckptB [ckptC...] --prompt ...` renders side-by-side panels (rich Columns) for qualitative mechanism comparison - same prompt, same seed, same sampling params;
- mechanism coverage: all KV-cache-supporting mechanisms; gauge produces a clear error naming bead A5 until that lands (then include it);
- deterministic mode: greedy + fixed seed must produce identical output across runs (regression-testable).

EXPECTATION SETTING (docs): checkpoints at this scale generate barely-coherent text; the point is (a) the plumbing works end-to-end, (b) RELATIVE comparisons between mechanisms at matched budgets, (c) decode-path validation in anger. Say this in the command help and README so nobody judges the math by a 2M-param model's prose.

ACCEPTANCE:
- Works on a tiny CPU checkpoint for >= 9 mechanisms; determinism test green (greedy same-seed byte-identical output);
- tokens/s reported per mechanism in a comparison table when using --compare;
- README Quick Tour gains a sampling step;
- Smoke test in CI-lite (tiny fixture checkpoint from C2's golden fixture, 16 tokens).

DEPENDS ON: D1 (checkpoint loading).

WHY: this project sits on a four-way version matrix (Python 3.13 + JAX + PyTorch + CUDA, plus parquet data presence and tokenizer availability). The README's Troubleshooting section exists precisely because onboarding hits these failure modes; a doctor command converts that support burden into 30 seconds of self-service - and gives agents a reliable preflight before launching expensive benchmark suites.

WHAT: `mgr doctor [--json]` performing, with a rich table of check/status/detail/fix-hint per row:
- Python version (require 3.13+), uv presence, venv active;
- torch version, CUDA availability, device name/memory, bf16 support; MPS detection on macOS;
- JAX version, backend, device list (get_device_info() in utils.py already exists - reuse);
- Triton importability (A7 prerequisite);
- training data: parquet files present in NANOCHAT_BASE_DIR (dataset.list_parquet_files), count vs --min-parquet-files default, auto-download hint if missing;
- tokenizer loads; tiktoken/tokenizers versions;
- disk space at NANOCHAT_BASE_DIR and artifacts/;
- SMOKE: forward pass of the tiniest GPT config on the detected device (catches broken installs that import fine);
- exit code: 0 all green, 1 warnings, 2 failures (scriptable preflight).

Every failed row carries an actionable fix-it hint (the exact uv/env command), matching the rich-console philosophy in CLAUDE.md.

ACCEPTANCE:
- Runs < 30s on CPU-only environment; --json output schema for agent consumption;
- Test asserts it runs green in CI environment and that a simulated missing-data condition produces the right hint + exit code;
- README Troubleshooting section updated to lead with "run mgr doctor".

WHY: the project's wow is currently distributed across a dozen CLI commands and a 41KB README. The cheapest adoption asset any research repo can ship is ONE command that delivers the pitch in five minutes on a laptop CPU - watch two mathematically different transformers train, see their invariants CERTIFIED, see them generate side by side, read a comparison table. rz8.8's Scenario 1 is the TEST version of this loop (assertions, SIGKILL/resume, exhaustive failure forensics); quickstart is the USER version (curated, pretty, fast, zero required flags). Existing bead 9f1 (pedagogical walkthrough) is the DEPTH dial on individual JAX demos; quickstart is the BREADTH tour of the production story - coordinate, do not duplicate.

WHAT: `mgr quickstart [--budget-seconds 300] [--mechanisms standard,tropical] [--device auto] [--seed S] [--offline]` (extend cli.py IN PLACE):
1. STAGES, each a rich panel with elapsed time and a one-sentence "what you are seeing" caption:
   (a) compact doctor preflight (reuse rz8.7's checks, condensed rendering);
   (b) generate a tiny diagnostic task (vdc.1's smallest config) - doubles as offline training data;
   (c) train the chosen mechanisms at a seconds-scale budget with live loss sparklines;
   (d) mgr certify on both checkpoints - the "the math is verified, live, on the model you just trained" moment (this is the project's signature; give it the best panel);
   (e) side-by-side generation via rz8.5 --compare (same prompt, same seed);
   (f) mini comparison table: final loss, tokens/s, one mechanism-specific diagnostic each (e.g. tropical gamma margin), certificate status;
   (g) closing panel: pointers to README sections, the docs site (swh.2 when live), and the natural next commands (bench-fixed-flops, eval-tasks, scorecard).
2. EXPECTATION SETTING built into the output (rz8.5's lesson, stated charmingly): seconds-scale models generate gibberish; the demo shows the PIPELINE and the CERTIFICATES, not language ability - say it before the samples render, so nobody judges the math by a 60-second model's prose.
3. BUDGET HONESTY: --budget-seconds adapts step counts to the host (calibrating from the first N step timings); default completes < 5 minutes on a 4-core CPU (measured on CI hardware, bound recorded and asserted with margin); --offline uses the generated task as training data so the wow needs NO network and NO FineWeb download.
4. SURFACING: README Quick Start leads with this command; mgr doctor's all-green output suggests it as the next step; the docs site quickstart page mirrors it.

TESTS & LOGGING: e2e smoke in CI-lite (tiny budget; asserts every stage completes, exit 0, expected artifacts present under the run dir); stage-failure forensics test (deliberately break one stage - e.g. corrupt the generated task - assert the failure panel names the stage, shows the subprocess tail, and prints the exact reproduction command; inherits rz8.8's logging discipline); runtime-budget assertion (completes within the documented bound on CI hardware with safety margin); seed logged and settable (determinism not REQUIRED for a demo, but reproducibility on request is); --offline path tested with no data directory present; output reviewed for rich-styling quality per CLAUDE.md (this command IS the project's first impression - polish is a requirement, not a nicety).

DEPS: rz8.5 (hard - side-by-side sampling is the centerpiece; transitively brings rz8.1 checkpointing), vdc.1 (hard - task generation supplies both the diagnostic stage and offline training data); parent swh epic. RELATION: rz8.7 doctor (preflight, closed), 5ki.1 certify (closed), rz8.8 (the test-grade sibling - share stage plumbing where natural, never share the curated output code), 9f1 (depth-dial sibling), swh.2 (docs-site mirror), README.
REFINEMENT (plan-space pass): DEFAULT DATA DECISION (UX-critical) - the generated diagnostic task from stage (b) IS the default training data, always: it is deterministic, seconds-fast to build, and removes the single biggest failure mode (a fresh user without the FineWeb parquet download would otherwise hit a wall inside the showcase command). This makes the previously-described --offline flag redundant - REPLACE it with an optional --data DIR flag for users who want the showcase to run on their real parquet instead. Consequence for the script: stage (b) is unconditionally required (it feeds training, eval, and the sampling prompts); the no-data-directory test becomes the DEFAULT path test, and the --data path gets its own smoke. Expectation-setting text updates accordingly (the model learns a toy task, not language - which is exactly why the certificates, not the prose, are the star).
